VIII.

In this passage. and especially at the beginning, the sen- tences are very short and terse. In compound tenses the auxiliary verb is constantly omitted, a favourite practice with Livy, for which you must always be prepared.

l. Patres conscripti, i.e. patre-3 et conscripti. This was the regular form used in addressing the Senate. The Patres were the senators in the time of the kings. After the expulsion of the Tarquius new senators were added, who were called conscripti, “ the cho=en ones.''
